   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1833-10_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Albemarle-Street_ENK"/>Albemarle Street
                  <date when="1833-10-15">Oct<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 15</date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>Dear Madam</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I am desired by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">Mr<lb/>
               Murray</persName> to acquaint you that if<lb/>
               his is intention to publish at<lb/>
               Christmas a little story of yours<lb/>
               wch appeared some time ago<lb/>
               in the work called the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Chris1">Xmas Box</title>.<lb/>
               The copyright of which he purchased<lb/>
               from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AinsW1">Mr. Ainsworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have taken the liberty of enclosing<lb/>
               a set of the proof sheets in case you<lb/>
               have any remarks to make on them<lb/>
               a <del>sheet</del> tale by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">Mr. Lockhart</persName>, extracted<lb/>
               tracted from the same publication<lb/>
               from the same publication<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1833-10_page02.jpg"/>
               is intended to accompany it<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">Mr Murray</persName> directs me to let<lb/>
               you know that he has still in<lb/>
               his case the MS. by the author of<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Berth1">Bertha</title>, but is not sufficiently<lb/>
               confident of the result of its <choice>
                  <orig>pub-<lb/>
               lication</orig>
                  <reg>publication</reg>
               </choice> to venture to undertake<lb/>
               it, especially at a moment like<lb/>
               this, so unfavourable to literature<lb/>
               generally - He wishes to enquire<lb/>
               whether it would be possible to<lb/>
               throw into another shape, the <choice>
                  <orig>in-<lb/>
               formation</orig>
                  <reg>information</reg>
               </choice>
               <choice>
                  <orig>wch</orig>
                  <reg>which</reg>
               </choice> it contains, also<lb/>
               to ask whether the author has any<lb/>
               thoughts of continuing <title ref="./Workography.xml#Berth1">Bertha's<lb/>
               Journal</title> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1833-10_page03.jpg"/>
               I shall esteem it a great favour<lb/>
               to receive a reply to this at<lb/>
               your leisure<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I am dear Madam<lb/>
               Your most obedient servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ3">J Murray <choice>
                     <orig>Jun<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                     </orig>
                     <reg>Junior</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1833-10_page04.jpg"/>
                  <addrLine>1832</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ3">J Murray</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
